#: data/functions.xml.in:1210
msgid ""
"Returns a value from an expression using the specified number base (radix). "
"For bases between -62 and 62 full mathematical expressions (including "
"operators and functions) are supported, while for other bases the specified "
"expression is converted to a single number.\n"
"\n"
"Bases ≤ 36 use digits 0-9 and A-Z (case insensitive).\n"
"\n"
"Bases between 37 and 62 uses case sensitive letters (0-9, A-Z, a-z) as "
"digits ('z' equals 61).\n"
"\n"
"Bases over 62 use Unicode characters as digits, with the character code as "
"value (e.g. '0' equals 48). Escaped characters are in this case supported "
"(e.g. '\\0' = 0, '\\523' = 523, '\\x7f' = 127).\n"
"\n"
"Negative bases use the same digits as the corresponding positive bases and "
"the digits used for non-integer bases are determined by rounding the base "
"away from zero. Bases that are not real numbers by default use digits 0-9 "
"and A-Z.\n"
"\n"
"The set of digits used can be selected using the third argument (defaults to "
"0 for automatic selection). Set it to 1 for digits 0-9 and A-Z, 2 for 0-9, A-"
"Z and a-z, 3 for Unicode digits, and 4 for phonewords (e.g. ABC=2, DEF=3, "
"etc.), or enter a text string with all digits placed in ascending order "
"(e.g. \"0123456789\") and optionally separated by semicolon (to enable "
"multiple equivalent digits, e.g. \"0;aA1;bB2;cC3\"). When the set of digits "
"is manually selected, the specified expression is always converted to a "
"single number."
msgstr ""

